}}'''Dame Nancy Jane Rothwell''', [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]], [[Academy of Medical Sciences|FMedSci]] (born 2 October 1955)<ref>''Who's Who in Greater Manchester''; golden jubilee edition. Manchester: Manchester Literary & Philosophical Society, 2002; p. 313</ref> is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[physiologist]] and [[academic]] who became the President and Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Manchester]] in July 2010,<ref>[http://www.manchester.ac.uk/aboutus/news/display/?id=5874 New President and Vice-Chancellor for the University of Manchester]</ref> having been Deputy President and Deputy Vice-Chancellor since January 2010. Rothwell is also a director of pharmaceuticals company [[AstraZeneca]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://people.forbes.com/profile/dame-nancy-rothwell/8087 | work=Forbes}}</ref> co-chair of the [[Council for Science and Technology]] and President of the [[Society of Biology]].<ref name="mancunion">{{cite web |url=http://mancunion.com/2013/02/25/dame-nancy-rothwell-qa/ |title=As it happened: Q&A with Professor Dame Nancy Rothwell > The Mancunion |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>Brown, Matthew (September 2004) "A Society Fellow", in: ''AUTlook''. Association of University Teachers; no. 231, pp. 24-25.</ref><ref name="newstatesman">{{cite web |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/education/2010/10/manchester-university-science |title=The New Statesman Interview: Nancy Rothwell, vice-chancellor, Manchester University |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref name="Society of Biology">{{cite web |url=http://www.societyofbiology.org/aboutus/who-we-are/council |title=Society of Biology Council and Officers |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref>

==Education==
She was born at [[Tarleton]], near Preston, Lancashire, and educated at [[Penwortham]] Girlsâ€™ Grammar School. She enrolled at the [[University of London]] and obtained a first class degree in [[Physiology]] (1976) and a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree (1979)<ref>{{cite thesis|degree=PhD|first=Nancy Jane|last=Rothwell|title=Physiological mechanisms involved in the regulation of energy balance|publisher=Kings College London|date=1979|url=http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=22&uin=uk.bl.ethos.471044|authorlink=Nancy Rothwell}}</ref> from [[Queen Elizabeth College]] London. She was awarded a [[Doctor of Science]] degree (1987) by [[King's College London]]. She was awarded an Honorary Degree (Doctor of Laws) from the [[University of Bath]] in 2009.

==Research==
Dame Nancy's early research<ref name="microsoft">{{AcademicSearch|18102816}}</ref><ref>{{cite pmid| 551265}}</ref><ref>{{cite pmid| 7537419}}</ref><ref>{{cite pmid| 7754524}}</ref> identified mechanisms of energy balance regulation, [[obesity]] and [[cachexia]].<ref>{{cite pmid|9109835}}</ref> In 1984 she was awarded a Royal Society Research Fellowship and relocated to [[Victoria University of Manchester|Manchester]] in 1987 and numerous grants by the [[Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council|BBSRC]].<ref name="bbsrc">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbsrc.ac.uk/PA/grants/PersonDetails.aspx?Personid=13650 |title=Grants awarded to Nancy Rothwell by the BBSRC |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref> She was appointed to a chair in Physiology in 1994, then a prestigious [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]] Research Chair in 1998. Her current research focuses on the role of inflammation in brain disease and has identified the role of the cytokine [[interleukin]]-1 (IL-1)<ref>{{cite doi|10.1016/0361-9230(92)90033-T}}</ref> in diverse forms of brain injury.<ref>{{cite doi|10.1038/35094583}}</ref> Her recent studies have begun to elucidate the mechanisms regulating IL-1 release and its action, and her group has conducted the first early clinical trial of an IL-1 inhibitor in strokes. She served as president of the [[British Neuroscience Association]]  and a council member of [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council (MRC)]].

From October 2004 she was vice-president for research of the University.<ref name="whowantstobe">{{cite book |author=Rothwell, Nancy |title=Who wants to be a scientist?: choosing science as a career |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge, UK |year=2002 |pages= |isbn=0-521-52092-4 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=|authorlink=Nancy Rothwell}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://education.guardian.co.uk/manchesteruniversityunited/story/0,,1332549,00.html| title=Manchester voices--Nancy Rothwell |author=Cripps, Elizabeth|accessdate=2011-04-05|location=London|work=The Guardian}}</ref> Rothwell in 2010 was overseeing a research group of about 20 scientists, with significant external funding and was announced to succeed [[Alan Gilbert (Australian academic)|Alan Gilbert]] as President and Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Manchester]] on 1 July 2010. She is a Trustee of [[Cancer Research UK]], the Campaign for Medical Progress, a Council member of [[BBSRC]], Chair of the [[Research Defence Society]] and the [[Wellcome Trust]] Public Engagement Strategy Committee, and a non-executive director of [[AstraZeneca]]. In 1998 she delivered the [[Royal Institution Christmas Lectures|Royal Institution Christmas Lecture]] on ''The Secrets of Life'', televised by the [[BBC]].<ref>[http://richannel.org/christmas-lectures-1998-nancy-rothwell--times-of-our-lives Christmas Lectures 1998: Nancy Rothwell] - Times of our lives</ref>

In 2003 she won the prestigious Pfizer Research Prize,<ref>[http://www.royalsoc.ac.uk/page.asp?tip=1&id=4215 Pfizer Research Prize]</ref> and in 2004 was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS).<ref>[http://education.guardian.co.uk/higher/profile/story/0,,1740748,00.html Guardian profile of Nancy Rothwell]</ref> In 2005 she was made a [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]].

In January 2010 she was appointed Deputy President and Deputy Vice-Chancellor: until Alan Gilbert retired she was acting President due to his sick leave. On 21 June 2010, she was appointed President and Vice-Chancellor of the University of Manchester. She assumed her post on 1 July 2010, succeeding Professor Alan Gilbert, who had retired after nearly six years. Dame Nancy became the first woman to lead the University of Manchester or either of its two predecessor institutions. Commenting on her appointment, Dame Nancy said: "I am honoured and delighted to be invited to lead the University at this exciting time. I am determined to maintain the strategic focus that we have developed over the past six years and to work closely with colleagues to identify new priorities and opportunities for the University in the very challenging external environment that we will face over the next few years."

Chairman of the Appointment Panel and Chairman-elect of the University's Board of Governors Mr Anil Ruia said: "Dame Nancy will bring her own distinctive strengths, perspective and style to the role of President and Vice-Chancellor which will enable the University to build upon the remarkable progress that we have made under Professor Alan Gilbert's leadership." In 2009 Nancy Rothwell become President of the newly formed [[Society of Biology]].

In February 2013 she was assessed as the 15th most powerful woman in the United Kingdom by [[Woman's Hour]] on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007qlvb/features/power-list-100 |title=BBC Radio 4 - Woman's Hour - The Power List 2013 |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01qj7jd/profiles/nancy-rothwell |title=BBC Radio 4 - Woman's Hour, Woman's Hour Power List - Professor Dame Nancy Rothwell |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref>

